\b \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Fandango
\b0  is a lively couples {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dance"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 dance}} from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spain"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Spain}}, usually in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triple_metre"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 triple metre}}, traditionally accompanied by guitars and castanets or hand-clapping ("palmas" in Spanish). Fandango can both be sung and danced. Sung fandango is usually bipartite: it has an instrumental introduction followed by "variaciones". Sung fandango usually follows the structure of "cante" that consist of four or five {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octosyllabic"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 octosyllabic}} verses (coplas) or musical phrases (tercios). Occasionally, the first copla is repeated.\cf0 \cb1 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 \
