\b \cf5 \strokec5 Classical music
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 The form of Fandango have been used by many European composers, and often included in stage and instrumental works. Notable examples include J.-P. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rameau"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Rameau}}'s "Les trois mains" ( in "Nouvelles suites de pi\'e8ces de clavecin", ca.1729\'9630); {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domenico_Scarlatti"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Domenico Scarlatti}}'s "Fandango portugu\'e9s" (K 492, 1756) and "Fandango del SigR Escarlate". Fandango forms #19 in the part 2 of Gluck's ballet {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Juan"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Don Juan}} (1761); it appears also in the third-act finale of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mozart"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Mozart}}'s opera {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_nozze_di_Figaro"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Le nozze di Figaro}} (1786); in the finale of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luigi_Boccherini"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Luigi Boccherini}}'s String Quartet op.40 no.2 (1798); {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Soler"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Antonio Soler}}'s Fandango for harpsichord; and the finale of Rimsky-Korsakov's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capriccio_Espagnol"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Capriccio Espagnol}}. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luis_de_Freitas_Branco"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Luis de Freitas Branco}}'s third movement of his "Suite Alentejana no. 1" is inspired on the popular fandango of the regions of Alentejo and Ribatejo.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl460\sa90\partightenfactor0

\b \cf5 \strokec5 Spanish dance
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa140\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 The current 3/4 pattern of the fandango, its distinctive progression (i\'96iv\'96V) lyrics with octosyllabic verses and the use of castanets and guitars are well-documented from the 18th century.\
The 
\i fandangos grandes
\i0  (big fandangos) are normally danced by couples, which start out slowly with gradually increasing tempo. Many varieties are derived from this one.\
The 
\i fandanguillos
\i0  (little fandangos) are livelier, more festive derivations of fandangos. Some regions of Spain have developed their own style of fandangos, such as 
\i Huelva
\i0  (fandangos de Huelva) 
\i and M\'e1laga
\i0  (fandangos de M\'e1laga
\i , or
\i0  Verdiales)
\i . Northern areas such as the Asturias Principality of Asturias, the Basque Country and Castile and Le\'f3nCastile have preserved a more relaxed performance.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl460\sa90\partightenfactor0

\i0\b \cf5 \strokec5 Portuguese dance
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa140\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 Although Spanish in origin, Fandango is one of the main folk dances in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portugal"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Portugal}}. The choreography is quite simple: on its more frequent setting two male dancers face each other, dancing and tap-dancing one at each time, showing which one has the most lightness and repertoire of feet changes in the tap-dancing. The dancers can be boy and girl, boy and boy (most frequent) or rarely two girls. While one of the dancers dances, the other just "goes along". Afterwards, they "both drag their feet for a while" until the other one takes his turn. They stay there, disputing, seeing which one of them makes the feet transitions more eye-catching.\
The "fandango do Ribatejo" refers specifically the form of fandango practiced in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ribatejo_Province"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Ribatejo}}, Portugal. The dance is usually performed by two {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campino"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Campinos}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl460\sa90\partightenfactor0

